	<figcaption><small>Multiple Choice vs. Select Menu</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>While not all portions of this project presented many challneges there were a couple that had to be addressed. The screenshots displayed above show a multiple choice selection for the quiz. While having multiple choice is completely acceptable, it also presents a problem for smaller screens and requires more cognitive overhead for the user to scroll and search for answers where real-estate is at a premium. In that vein we opted for a select emnu making it easier on the user and keeping them isolated within the space they are present in.</p>

<p>This decision also made it simple for developers to cater to and not requiring any fancy shuffling or maneuvering to switch from a select on mobile to mc on larger screens. With this approach its a one size fits all solution.</p>

<figure class="figure-site" style="width: 100%;margin: auto;">
	<div class="flex-inline">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/results-stacked.png" alt="">
		<img src="{{site.imgdir}}clients/truth-collective/results-column.png" alt="">
	</div>
	<figcaption><small>Results Screens and Variations</small></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Variations of the results screen required critical thinking and consideration regarding different layouts and scenarios. It was imperative to look at diffrent approaches of displaying information that remained beneficial for readability, but also made sense from an information hierarchy perspective. For the results with information stacked we decided smaller contexts would have the ability to swipe, or click to the next result saving screen real estate, and avoiding the user from scrolling.</p>

<p>The column approach allowed for easy scanning of the data from left to right, but in smaller contexts the information would be displayed as a single column. In this case we decided to hyper link to the CTAs just under the first result allowing users to click this hyper link that automatically scrolls the user to the CTAs efficiently and intuitively.</p>

